english:
  title: Ode on the Artificial Stone Mountain
  author: Sung Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There was once a great man, a sage,
    who took heaven and earth as his cottage,
    the six directions as his screen,
    smoke and clouds as his weather,
    rivers and seas as his heart.

    The sighing wind became his zither,
    flowering trees and singing birds his servants.
    With cunning craft from his mind's forge
    he carved the stark bones of mountains,
    and suddenly conjured a realm
    where east and west dissolve.

    The forms rose jagged and sheer—
    some carved like cliffs, some layered smooth,
    some towering sharp, some softly rounded.
    Now coiling, now spreading,
    horizontal, vertical, rising in steps like temple stairs,
    or clustering sharp as sword points.
    Some spread like sacred vessels,
    some stood like bamboo poles.

    Some soared like hunting hawks,
    some crouched like prowling beasts.
    One seemed a bird with lifted head,
    another a scorpion's arching tail.
    Here a tall official's hat,
    there sleeves torn and gaping,
    heels and elbows bare as if exposed,
    beards and hair wild and loose.
    Patterns like ancient script or oracle bones
    burned dark in flame.

    Blocked yet flowing through,
    seemingly quarreling yet touching.
    Bowing as if in courtesy,
    meeting as if in greeting.
    Racing like galloping steeds,
    straining like drawn bows—
    yet needing no gods to carve the Nine-Fold pass,
    no sage-king to channel waters.

    The summit stands like a parent's majesty,
    the lesser peaks kneel in filial grace.
    In shadowed valleys, dark and still,
    flowers bloom serene as lotus blooms.
    Chasms and crevasses become new walls,
    windings create ramparts.

    Varied hues dapple the stone—
    blue and crimson interspersed.
    Fragrant with mist, luxuriant and lush,
    the grasses wave and flowers sway.
    When sunrise kindles it, all blazes bright,
    when moonlight finds it, all shimmers fine.
    Frost makes it cut more keen,
    rain makes its colors deepen.

    Hazy smoke wreathes up slowly,
    wrapping half its slopes.
    Clouds seem to gather here
    as dragons ride the wind through phantom realms.
    Flocks of cranes appear to nest
    among the immortal pines.
    A world of dust transcended,
    such traces rare in human times.

    High and low, near and far,
    large and small merge without seam—
    ten thousand forms yet all one form,
    many aspects yet all harmony.

    Then came a visitor to the sage and spoke:
    "I have heard that ornate decoration destroys simplicity,
    that fattened beasts corrupt the truest taste,
    that false gems cloud true jade's light,
    that fragrant mimics taint the orchid's scent.
    What I behold today bewilders all my senses—
    I cannot tell if this is but a child's play
    wherein the demons show abundance to mock us,
    or if sprites and spirits, on stormy nights,
    have stolen heaven's axe and moon's chisel
    to carve and polish this marvel that astounds me so."

    The sage replied: "Not so.
    When we consider the small, even our liver and gall are not our own.
    When we consider the great, heaven and earth cannot contain us.
    A thousand miles begins at an inch,
    growing ever distant.
    Ten thousand things spring from the infinitesimal,
    yet know no bound.

    Those mountain ridges stretching endlessly—
    they are the weight of Taihangshan and Wangwushan.
    Those peaks standing alone and steep—
    they are Tianzhushan and Zhurong's summits.
    Waters cascading in torrents—
    they are Dragon Gate's rapids.
    Waters pooled in clarity—
    they are Dongting and Yunmeng's vastness.

    Cliffs and shoals where the eye bends downward—
    these are Dabie and Xiaobie's glories,
    Chibi and Wuxi's majesty.

    Consider thus:
    a pebble becomes Taishan,
    a handful of water becomes the great rivers.
    A leaf-boat spinning slowly
    becomes a thousand-ton vessel riding the wind.
    Tiny fish darting and leaping
    become the great whales and turtles churning the sky.

    So what is false and what is true?
    What shall we abandon, what shall we seek?
    Clumsy is not always clumsy,
    skilled is not always skilled.
    Deception holds no deceit,
    truth holds no truth.
    Darkness brings no foolishness,
    clarity brings no wisdom.

    Human fate has its rise and fall,
    the Way has its corruption and purity.
    Why grieve at gain,
    why sorrow at loss?

    Better to wander free,
    to merge one's heart with the spirit,
    to ride the phoenix through the void
    and transcend all this realm—
    why strive for the Moon Palace or the Jade Pools,
    or trudge through thorns in wooden clogs?

    Once Zixu followed Wangshigong,
    composing rhapsodies of Shanglinyuan to please the Han court.
    Though that age boasted of Qi and exaggerated Chu,
    swallowing eight or nine Yunmeng lakes in its breast,
    today I sit and gaze
    within these humble walls,
    confronting clouds and mountains
    in the quiet of my room.

    My joy needs no bells or drums—
    it is the music of unbeaten drums.

    Alas! Those wrapped in silk and purple,
    scurrying about in worldly dust,
    are but maggots writhing in the dregs.

    Hearing this, my guest fell silent,
    held his breath, bowed low.
    We sat together on the same seat,
    then rose and walked away with canes in hand.
    Truly we shall renounce all gain and glory,
    transcend all worldly care,
    and walk together to life's end.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Five Recluses' (五丁) refers to legendary figures who carved a path through mountains by moving stone oxen, representing the transformation of natural obstacles into passage.
    - 'This celebrates the philosophical principle that all scale is relative: what appears vast can be found in miniature, and what seems small contains infinity.'
    - The references to famous Chinese mountains (Taishan, Zhurong) and rivers (Dragon Gate, Dongting Lake) represent the ideal landscape of classical Chinese aesthetics, suggesting that the artificial mountain contains the essence of all natural majesty.
